Estimating the Elasticity of Alcohol

AJ Montesa

2024-11-01

Using Household Expenditure Data

Family Income and Expenditure Survey (FIES)

The Family Income and Expenditure Survey (FIES) is a nationwide survey of households undertaken every three years by the Philippine Statistics Authority (PSA). It is the main source of data on family income and expenditure, which include among others, levels of consumption by item of expenditure as well as sources of income in cash and in kind. The results of FIES provide information on the levels of living and disparities in income of Filipino families, as well as their spending patterns.

Labor Force Survey (LFS)

The Labor Force Survey (LFS) is a nationwide survey of households conducted regularly to gather data on the demographic and socio-economic characteristics of the population. It is primarily geared towards the estimation of the levels of employment and unemployment in the country. It is conducted every first month of the quarter in selected areas in the Philippines.

Generating Unit Values / Prices

hes2012 <- hes2012 %>%
  mutate(uvbeer = tbeer/qtbeer, uvgin = tgin/qtgin, uvcigarette = tcigarette/qtcigarette,
         year = "2012",
         hhead_ms = str_c(hhead_ms)) %>%
  mutate(nonzero_beer = qtbeer>0, nonzero_gin = qtgin>0, nonzero_cigarette = qtcigarette>0)

hes2015 <- hes2015 %>%
  mutate(uvbeer = tbeer/qtbeer, uvgin = tgin/qtgin, uvcigarette = tcigarette/qtcigarette,
         year = "2015",
         hhead_ms = str_c(hhead_ms)) %>%
  mutate(nonzero_beer = qtbeer>0, nonzero_gin = qtgin>0, nonzero_cigarette = qtcigarette>0)

hes2018 <- hes2018 %>%
  mutate(uvbeer = tbeer/qtbeer, uvgin = tgin/qtgin, uvcigarette = tcigarette/qtcigarette,
         year = "2018",
         hhead_ms = str_c(hhead_ms)) %>%
  mutate(nonzero_beer = qtbeer>0, nonzero_gin = qtgin>0, nonzero_cigarette = qtcigarette>0)

hesPooled <- bind_rows(hes2012, hes2015, hes2018) %>%
  left_join(inflation_factors) %>%
  mutate(toinc_b18 = toinc/inflation_factor, ttotex_b18 = ttotex/inflation_factor,
         tbeer_b18 = tbeer/inflation_factor, tgin_b18 = tgin/inflation_factor, tcigarette_b18 = tcigarette/inflation_factor) %>%
  mutate(uvbeer = tbeer/qtbeer, uvgin = tgin/qtgin, uvcigarette = tcigarette/qtcigarette,
         uvbeer_b18 = tbeer_b18/qtbeer, uvgin_b18 = tgin_b18/qtgin, uvcigarette_b18 = tcigarette_b18/qtcigarette) %>%
  mutate(nonzero_beer = qtbeer>0, nonzero_gin = qtgin>0, nonzero_cigarette = qtcigarette>0)

Modeling Elasticity

Ordinary Least Squares

Beer

ols_beer <- log(qtbeer) ~ log(uvbeer) + log(toinc) + hhead_male + hhead_age + hhead_married + hhead_employed + members + I(members_adultmale/members) + region_label + urban

ols_beerPool <- log(qtbeer) ~ log(uvbeer_b18) + log(toinc_b18) + hhead_male + hhead_age + hhead_married + hhead_employed + members + I(members_adultmale/members) + region_label + urban + factor(year)


ols_b2012 <- lm(formula = ols_beer, data = hes2012, weights = rfact)

ols_b2015 <- lm(formula = ols_beer, data = hes2015, weights = rfact)

ols_b2018 <- lm(formula = ols_beer, data = hes2018, weights = rfact)

ols_bPool <- lm(ols_beerPool, data = hesPooled, weights = rfact)

Heckman Selection

To address selection bias in cases where data on the dependent variable is only available for a selected subset of the sample.

First step : Selection

A selection equation (binary outcome) that models whether an observation is selected (or observed). For elasticity, the first step models whether a household chooses to have a non-zero level of consumption for the commodities of interest. A probit model is conducted for the selection equation, and an inverse Mills ratio (IMR) is calculated from the results.

In selection model, an exclusion restriction variable included to predict selection but is not included in the final regression model. Exclusion restrictions are important because they help to avoid collinearity and produce credible estimates.

Second step : Outcome/Consumption

An outcome equation that models the actual dependent variable among those selected. Selection bias in the outcome equation is corrected by using the inverse Mills ratio obtained from the first step.

Beer

  • For the Two-Step Heckman Selection Model, the proportion of young children in the household members_age05_below as well as education level of the most-educated member in the household members_hgc are used as exclusionary restriction variables for the first stage.
# Beer Stage 1 Selection
heckman1_beer <- nonzero_beer ~ log(uvbeer) + log(toinc) + hhead_male + hhead_age + hhead_married + hhead_employed + members + I(members_adultmale/members) + region_label + urban + I(members_age05below/members) + members_hgc

heckman1_beerPool <- nonzero_beer ~ log(uvbeer_b18) + log(toinc_b18) + hhead_male + hhead_age + hhead_married + hhead_employed + members + I(members_adultmale/members) + region_label + urban + I(members_age05below/members) + members_hgc + factor(year)

stage1_vars <- c("nonzero_beer", "qtbeer", "uvbeer", "toinc", "hhead_male", "hhead_age", "hhead_married", "hhead_employed", "members", "members_adultmale", "region_label", "urban", "members_age05below", "members_hgc")

# Beer Stage 2 Outcome
heckman2_beer <- log(qtbeer) ~ log(uvbeer) + log(toinc) + hhead_male + hhead_age + hhead_married + hhead_employed +  members + I(members_adultmale/members) + region_label + urban + imr_beer

heckman2_beerPool <- log(qtbeer) ~ log(uvbeer_b18) + log(toinc_b18) + hhead_male + hhead_age + hhead_married + hhead_employed + members + I(members_adultmale/members) + region_label + urban + factor(year) + imr_beer


#### Beer 2012 - Heckman ####
# Stage 1 Selection Model
hm1_beer2012 <- glm(
  formula = heckman1_beer, data = hes2012, weights = rfact, family = binomial(link = 'probit')
)

# Calculate the inverse Mills ratio
lambda_beer <- predict(hm1_beer2012, type = "link")  # Linear predictor
imr_beer <- dnorm(lambda_beer) / pnorm(lambda_beer)  # Inverse Mills Ratio

# Add the inverse Mills ratio to the data
stage2_b2012 <- hes2012 %>%
  filter(if_all(.cols = all_of(stage1_vars), .fns = ~!is.na(.x))) %>%
  bind_cols(tibble(imr_beer = imr_beer))

# Stage 2 Outcome Model
hm2_b2012 <- lm(
  formula = heckman2_beer, data = stage2_b2012, weights = rfact, subset = (nonzero_beer == TRUE)
)

  formula = heckman2_cigarette, data = stage2_c2012, weights = rfact, subset = (nonzero_cigarette == TRUE)
)


#### Cigarette 2015 - Heckman ####
# Stage 1 Selection Model

  formula = heckman1_cigarette, data = hes2015, weights = rfact,
  family = binomial(link = 'probit')
)

# Calculate the inverse Mills ratio
lambda_cigarette <- predict(hm1_c2015, type = "link")  # Linear predictor
imr_cigarette <- dnorm(lambda_cigarette) / pnorm(lambda_cigarette)  # Inverse Mills Ratio

# Add the inverse Mills ratio to the data
stage2_c2015 <- hes2015 %>%
  filter(if_all(.cols = all_of(stage1_vars), .fns = ~!is.na(.x))) %>%
